  "prompt": "How can we check whether a number is prime or not?",
  "response": "To check whether a number \\( n \\) is prime, you can use the following steps:\n\n1. **Divisibility by 2:** If \\( n \\) is less than 2, it is not prime. If \\( n \\) equals 2, it is prime. If \\( n \\) is greater than 2 and is even (i.e., \\( n \\mod 2 = 0 \\)), it is not prime.\n\n2. **Divisibility by other numbers:** For odd \\( n \\) greater than 2:\n   - Check divisibility by all odd numbers from 3 up to the square root of \\( n \\). This is because if \\( n \\) can be divided by any number, then it can be expressed as \\( a \\times b \\). If both \\( a \\) and \\( b \\) were greater than the square root of \\( n \\), their product \\( a \\times b \\) would be greater than \\( n \\), which is a contradiction.\n\n   Steps:\n   - Calculate the square root of \\( n \\). Let's call this \\( \\sqrt{n} \\).\n   - Check if \\( n \\) is divisible by any odd number from 3 up to \\( \\sqrt{n} \\).\n\n   If \\( n \\) is not divisible by any of these numbers, then \\( n \\) is prime; otherwise, it is not.\n\nHere is a simple algorithm in pseudocode:\n\n```pseudocode\nfunction is_prime(n)\n    if n <= 1\n        return false\n    if n == 2\n        return true\n    if n % 2 == 0\n        return false\n    for i from 3 to sqrt(n) step 2\n        if n % i == 0\n            return false\n    return true\n```\n\nOr in Python:\n\n```python\nimport math\n\ndef is_prime(n):\n    if n <= 1:\n        return False\n    if n == 2:\n        return True\n    if n % 2 == 0:\n        return False\n    for i in range(3, int(math.sqrt(n)) + 1, 2):\n        if n % i == 0:\n            return False\n    return True\n```\n\nYou can test this function with various values to check for primality.",
